<page_title>Heat transfer</page_title>
<text>Heat transfer II

By Bob Tinker

What happens at the atomic level when a hot object is placed in contact with a cold one? Here, the green atoms start hot and the blue ones start cold. The graph at right plots the temperature of the green and blue atoms separately. What do you think you will observe on the graph? 

This model starts with about 50 pulses of heat in the upper atoms and the lower atoms almost at rest. The blue atoms are twice as massive than the green ones.

    
 
You may be surprised to see so much randomness in the graphs. Just look at the average trend and ignore the fluctuations. Can you explain the overall shape of the graphs and their final values? What do you predict if you start with fewer green atoms? 

If you turn on &quot;K.E. Shading,&quot; you can see which atoms are hot. You can add more heat with the red sun icon or remove heat with the ice cube next to it. You can remove some of the random spikes in the graph by clicking the fourth icon--the one that looks like a graph of staircase and a diagonal line.

There is a bit of gravity to hold everything in place.

The fluctuations occur because we are plotting the kinetic energy of the group of green or blue atoms. The average kinetic energy is the temperature, but for fewer than millions of atoms, the kinetic energy flucuates a lot. Each atom is rapidly exchanging energy between kinetic and potential forms. At one instant, an atom might have all its energy in potential form. This can happen when it moves far from equilibrium (giving it potential energy) and stopping (resulting in zero kinetic energy). Then very shortly later, the atom might zoom through equilibrium (where potential energy is zero) but very fast (with lots of kinetic energy). All atoms are making these exchanges all the time, so the sum of all their energies will show fluctuations. Only if there are millions of atoms will these fluctuations average out to a steady average which is the temperature.</text>
